	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=5845&mid=99019022887111>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=5845&mid=99019022887111>Improvement, not reduction.</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=5845&mid=99019022887111#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, May 18th 8:50 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=353><span id=Sage>Tehom</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>260 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.64]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>If the haste % was a reduction of delay, then yes, the delay would be zero. However, think of it as its name implies - an improvement in speed. What is a 100% speed improvement? Where X is the rate at which you hit: X + (1.00)X = 2X. Doubling. 200%? X + (2.00)X = 3X. Trippling. And so on. You can then either think of that as a multiplication on the delay (.5, .33, .25, etc), or you can just think of it as hitting appropriately faster.</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br><a href=HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=141703 target=akztarg>Tehom</a></td></tr>
